  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (environmental gap variant)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). The CPB device operates in clinical environments subject to temperature drift (18–28°C ambient), variable atmospheric pressure (e.g., high-altitude surgical suites at ~0.85 atm), and electromagnetic interference from adjacent imaging and electrosurgical equipment. These environmental parameters influence blood viscosity, pump motor torque, and sensor signal fidelity, yet all validation experiments were conducted under fixed laboratory conditions (22°C, 1 atm, no EM sources). No environmental-sensitivity study has been linked to the evidence package, and the operating envelope specification does not bound temperature, pressure, or EM exposure ranges.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Medium",
  "couName": "CPB use",
  "decision": "Accepted",
  "deviceClass": "Class II",
  "modelRiskLevel": 2,
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cpb-hemolysis-mrl2",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cpb-rh-lt1",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-centrifugal-pump-v3",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-piv-benchmark-dataset",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-hemolysis-lab-measurements"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-piv-baseline",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "PIV flow field comparison — laboratory baseline",
      "description": "Particle image velocimetry measurements acquired at 22°C, atmospheric pressure (1 atm), with no electromagnetic interference sources present. Five flow-speed operating points (2.0–5.0 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM) compared against CFD velocity fields; normalised RMS error < 8% across all planes. Validation conducted in a benchtop hydraulic loop isolated from clinical-environment EM sources. No temperature sweep, altitude simulation, or EM susceptibility testing was performed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-hemolysis-index",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative hemolysis index validation — controlled lab conditions",
      "description": "Hemolysis index measurements using bovine blood at 22°C and 1 atm ambient pressure across the same five operating points. RH values ranged 0.61–0.94 (all < 1.0). CFD-predicted RH matched within 12% of measured values. All experiments performed in a temperature-controlled laboratory at 22 ± 0.5°C; no variation in ambient pressure or EM environment was introduced. The sensitivity of blood viscosity (and hence shear-stress-driven hemolysis) to the 18–28°C clinical ambient range was not evaluated. No link to an environmental-sensitivity study exists in this evidence package."
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4037671",
